  'rw',
  'Some astronomers searching for extraterrestrial life have proposed that atmospheric NH (ammonia) can serve as a 3 biosignature gas-an indication that a planet harbors life. Jingcheng Huang, Sara Seager, and colleagues evaluated this possibility, finding that on rocky planets, atmospheric NH likely couldn''t reach detectably high levels in the absence of 3 biological activity. But the team also found that on so-called mini-Neptunes-gas planets smaller than Neptune but with atmospheres similar to Neptune''s-atmospheric pressure and temperature can be high enough to produce atmospheric NH 3. Based on the text, Huang, Seager, and colleagues would most likely agree with which statement about atmospheric NH ? 3 Its presence is more likely to indicate that a planet is a mini-Neptune than that the planet is a rocky planet that could',
  '[{"id":"a","text":"support life."},{"id":"b","text":"Its absence from a planet that''s not a mini-Neptune indicates that the planet probably doesn''t have life. It should be treated as a biosignature gas if detected in the atmosphere of a rocky planet but not if detected in the"},{"id":"c","text":"atmosphere of a mini-Neptune. It doesn''t reliably reach high enough concentrations in the atmospheres of rocky planets or mini-Neptunes to be"},{"id":"d","text":"treated as a biosignature gas."}]'::jsonb,
  'c',
  'Choice C is the best answer because it states a conclusion the researchers likely agree with, given the details in the text. The text explains that a biosignature gas is a gas that can be used as an indicator that a planet harbors some form of life and some astronomers have proposed that NH could serve as a biosignature gas. The researchers evaluating this claim 3 found that the atmosphere of rocky planets would be unlikely to reach "detectably high levels" of NH without biological 3 activity, which would support the proposal of NH serving as a biosignature gas. However, the text also states that mini- 3 Neptune planets can produce NH in the absence of biological activity. Thus, the text is structured to lead to the 3 conclusion that detectable levels of NH in the atmospheres of rocky planets could constitute a biosignature, but that is 3 not the case for detectable levels of the gas in the atmospheres of mini-Neptune planets. Choice A is incorrect because the text indicates that biological activity likely accounts for detectable levels of NH in the 3 atmospheres of rocky planets but mini-Neptune planets can have detectable levels of NH in their atmospheres in the 3 absence of biological activity. Therefore, both rocky planets and mini-Neptune planets can have detectable levels of atmospheric NH . Choice B is incorrect because the text states that for NH to reach detectable levels in the 3 3 atmospheres of rocky planets likely means they harbor biological activity, meaning that rocky planets with detectable NH usually harbor biological activity. However, that does not entail that every rocky planet with biological activity will 3 have detectable levels of NH in their atmospheres. Choice D is incorrect because the text claims only that some 3 astronomers have proposed using NH as a biosignature gas without mentioning a minimum concentration of 3 atmospheric NH that must be met for it to function as a biosignature gas. 3',
  'information-ideas',
